What is the measure, in degrees, of the supplement of an angle measuring $50$ degrees?
inference:
The supplement of an angle is $180$ degrees minus the angle.

Therefore, the supplement of an angle measuring $50$ degrees is $180 - 50 = 130$ degrees.

Final Answer: $\boxed{130}$. I hope it is correct.
ground_truth: Two supplementary angles add up to 180 degrees. Thus the supplement of 50 degrees is $180-50=\boxed{130}$ degrees.
